  "text": "The Kubernetes scheduler plugin framework is a sophisticated architecture for extensible pod scheduling. Here are the key components:\n\n**Framework Interface Definitions** (pkg/scheduler/framework/interface.go):\nThe Plugin interface (line 443) is the base interface all scheduling plugins must implement with a Name() method. The framework defines multiple plugin types:\n- PreEnqueuePlugin (line 452): Called before adding pods to the scheduling queue\n- QueueSortPlugin (line 464): Sorts pods in the scheduling queue\n- PreFilterPlugin (line 512): Initializes and validates pod scheduling prerequisites\n- FilterPlugin (line 540): Filters nodes where the pod cannot run (replaces 'predicates')\n- PostFilterPlugin (line 561): Handles preemption when no nodes pass filtering\n- PreScorePlugin (line 587): Informational extension point before scoring\n- ScorePlugin (line 607): Ranks nodes that passed filtering (replaces 'priorities')\n- ReservePlugin (line 624): Updates plugin state before binding\n- PreBindPlugin (line 640): Preparation before binding\n- PostBindPlugin (line 649): Cleanup after successful binding\n- PermitPlugin (line 660): Controls binding decisions\n- BindPlugin (line 673): Binds pods to nodes\n\nThe Framework interface (line 686) manages all plugins and coordinates the scheduling cycle through defined extension points.\n\n**Scheduler Orchestration** (pkg/scheduler/scheduler.go and pkg/scheduler/schedule_one.go):\nThe Scheduler struct (scheduler.go line 66) is the top-level component that watches for unscheduled pods and coordinates scheduling. It contains the scheduling queue, cache, and profiles. The Run method (scheduler.go line 464) starts the scheduler and runs a continuous scheduling loop by calling ScheduleOne in a dedicated goroutine.\n\nScheduleOne (schedule_one.go line 65) is the orchestration function that drives the complete scheduling cycle for a single pod. It retrieves a pod from the queue, attempts to find a suitable node, and handles failures through the framework's extension points.\n\n**Framework Runtime Implementation** (pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/framework.go):\nThe frameworkImpl struct (line 52) is the runtime implementation of the Framework interface, responsible for initializing and running scheduler plugins. It maintains slices of plugins for each extension point and coordinates their execution.\n\nRunFilterPlugins (line 872) invokes all registered filter plugins to determine which nodes are feasible for the pod. This replaces the 'predicate' concept from earlier Kubernetes versions.\n\nRunScorePlugins (line 1112) invokes all registered score plugins in parallel to rank the filtered nodes based on various scheduling criteria. This replaces the 'priority' concept.\n\n**Plugin Registry** (pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/registry.go and pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/registry.go):\nThe Registry type (runtime/registry.go line 71) is a map of plugin names to plugin factory functions. NewInTreeRegistry (plugins/registry.go line 47) builds the complete registry with all built-in plugins including DefaultBinder, TaintToleration, NodeAffinity, PodTopologySpread, NodeResources, VolumeBinding, and others. This function enables dynamic plugin registration and allows out-of-tree plugins to be added via the framework's extension mechanism.\n\nThe framework's modular plugin architecture allows Kubernetes deployments to customize scheduling behavior by enabling/disabling plugins and registering custom implementations at specific extension points."
